    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{4}{7} + \frac{19}{35}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{39}{35}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>7</m> and <m>35</m> is <m>35</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{4}{7}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>35</m>, we multiply <m>5</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned} \frac{4}{7} \amp = \frac{4 \cdot 5}{7 \cdot 5}\\ \amp  = \frac{20}{35} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>The second fraction already has the common denominator.</p>
<p>Finally, we can do the addition. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{4}{7} + \frac{19}{35}
        \amp = \frac{20}{35} + \frac{19}{35} \\
        \amp = \frac{20 + 19}{35} \\
        \amp = \frac{39}{35}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{39}{35}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
